I"1<p>A few months ago the lovely people at Sirdar kindly sent me some of their gorgeous Imagination yarn to try out. It is a soft, chunky weight yarn made from 100% acrylic and comes in 8 different colour ways. I had 4 balls of ‘Moonriver’ which is a mixture of blues, pinks, purples and greens, as we are still in the depths of winter here in the UK I decided to make myself a new scarf – I knew that it would be incredibly soft and cosy to wear.</p>

<p><img class="rounded img-fluid post-img mx-auto d-block" src="/assets/images/IMG_3150-1-768x768.jpeg" /></p>

<p>I am thrilled with the finished scarf which is made using a simple v-stitch, I have included the pattern below. I would definitely recommend this yarn, the photos do not do it’s pretty colour justice and I absolutely loved its soft texture – a pleasure to work with!</p>

<p><strong>Imagination Scarf Pattern</strong></p>

<p>What you’ll need:</p>

<ul>
  <li>3 balls of Sirdar Imagination Chunky</li>
  <li>7mm crochet hook</li>
  <li>scissors</li>
  <li>darning needle</li>
</ul>

<p>Abbreviations:</p>

<ul>
  <li>ch – Chain</li>
  <li>st – Stitch</li>
  <li>tr – Treble Crochet (US Double Crochet)</li>
</ul>

<p>Pattern is written in UK terms.</p>

<p>——————–</p>

<p>Chain 37</p>

<p>Row 1 – tr into 5th chain from the hook, ch1, tr into same stitch, *skip 2 ch, (tr, ch1, tr) in next st, repeat from * across until you have 2 ch left, tr in last ch, turn.</p>

<p>Row 2 – ch3, *(tr, ch1, tr) in ch1 space, repeat from * across to end, tr in top of ch3, turn.</p>

<p>Row 3 to 80 – Repeat Row 2.</p>

<p>Fasten off leaving a long tail for sewing together. Using a darning needle sew the short ends of the scarf together and then weave in the ends to finish.</p>

